  <refnamediv>
    <refname>&dhpackage;</refname>

    <refpurpose>A utility to manage your Lampadas back-end database.</refpurpose>
  </refnamediv>
  <refsynopsisdiv>
    <cmdsynopsis>
      <command>&dhpackage;</command>
	  <group>
	   	<arg><option>-h</option></arg>
	   	<arg><option>--help</option></arg>
	  </group>
	  <arg choice="req"><replaceable>ACTION</replaceable></arg>
	  <arg choice="req"><replaceable>DATABASE</replaceable></arg>
    </cmdsynopsis>
  </refsynopsisdiv>
  <refsect1>
    <title>DESCRIPTION</title>

    <para>This manual page documents the 
	<command>&dhpackage;</command> command.</para>

    <para><command>&dhpackage;</command> is utility to help you create, back up,
	restore, and manage the back-end database in which your Lampadas data is stored.
	Currently, only the PostgreSQL database is supported.</para>

	<para>Running <command>&dhpackage;</command> requires you to have the
	appropriate permissions to the database.</para>

  </refsect1>
  <refsect1>
    <title>ACTIONS</title>

	<para>The following actions can be specified on the command line,
	and will be executed against the database that you specify.</para>

	<caution><para>
	Some of these commands are destructive, and will destroy any data that
	exists in the specified database. Before executing any of these commands,
	you should back up your database.
	</para></caution>
	
	<cmdsynopsis><arg>create</arg></cmdsynopsis>

	<blockquote>
	<para>
	Create the data tables in the specified database.
	Note that this command does not actually create the database itself;
	for that, you should use the <command>createdb</command> command that
	is included in PostgreSQL.
	</para>
	</blockquote>

	<cmdsynopsis><arg>delete</arg></cmdsynopsis>
	
	<blockquote>
	<para>
	Delete the data in the specified database.
	</para>
	</blockquote>

	<cmdsynopsis><arg>load</arg></cmdsynopsis>
	
	<blockquote>
	<para>
	Load data that was backed up using the save action.
	</para>
	</blockquote>

	<cmdsynopsis><arg>save</arg></cmdsynopsis>
	
	<blockquote>
	<para>
	Save the data in your Lampadas database to text files. The files
	are written using the <command>COPY [..] TO</command> SQL statement,
	and are written to the <filename role="directory">/tmp</filename>
	directory.
	</para>
	</blockquote>

  </refsect1>
